## 3. GitHub Ecosystem — What Exists, What's Broken, What to Steal

### 3.1 ShortGPT (`RayVentura/ShortGPT`)
**What it is**: Framework for automating *creation* of short-form video content. It uses LLM + Editing Markup Language + JSON to produce automated YouTube Shorts/TikToks.

**What it does well**:
- JSON/EML-based operation schema (steal this concept)
- Automated engines: `ContentShortEngine`, `ContentVideoEngine`, `ContentTranslationEngine`
- ElevenLabs voice synthesis integration
- TinyDB for persistence of automated editing variables

**What's broken**:
- Completely cloud-dependent, no local inference
- Can only generate content *from scratch*, cannot edit user's own footage
- No undo system, no DAG. If it fails, you restart.
- No non-technical user interface — requires API keys and Python knowledge
- No object isolation (can't say "blur face of person on the left")

**What to steal**: 
> ✅ The JSON operation schema idea — a registry of ~200 named edit operations that map to structured JSON commands. This is the correct architecture for the NLP layer.

---

### 3.2 InstructPix2Pix (`timothybrooks/instruct-pix2pix`) + Grounded variant (`arthur-71/Grounded-Instruct-Pix2Pix`)

**What it is**: Image editing from written instructions. Two-conditioning diffusion model (image + text instruction → edited image). Doesn't require per-example fine-tuning.

**How it works**:
- Combines a language model (GPT-3/GPT-4) + Stable Diffusion
- Generates a large paired dataset (original image, instruction, edited image) then trains on it
- At inference: takes `(image, instruction)` and outputs `edited_image` in seconds

**Grounded variant adds**:
- CLIP-Score Filtering to extract noun phrases from instruction → find editing target
- Grounded-SAM to generate a precise segmentation mask of target
- Latent blending — only the masked area changes, preserving the rest of the image

**What's broken**:
- Forward pass model — it generates new pixels, doesn't track what changed
- Known failure modes: can't change viewpoints, struggles with object swap/reorganize
- No temporal consistency — apply it 500 frames → flickering artifact
- No undo history — the edit is baked in

**What to steal**:
> ✅ The two-stage pipeline: **Ground (isolate target with SAM2) → Edit (apply instruction to masked region)**. This is exactly the right architecture for your Image Worker.
> ✅ Latent blending for masked edits — ensures the unedited region remains pixel-perfect.

---

### 3.3 AnyV2V (`TIGER-AI-Lab/AnyV2V`)

**What it is**: A tuning-free framework for temporal consistency in video editing. Published at TMLR 2024.

**How it works** (two steps):
1. Edit the **first frame** of the video using any image editor (InstructPix2Pix, Grounded-IP2P, etc.)
2. Use an image-to-video (I2V) model with **temporal feature injection** to propagate the edit to all remaining frames

**Why temporal consistency matters**:
- Naive frame-by-frame editing → flickering between frames (character changes shirt color slightly every frame)
- AnyV2V's anchor approach locks visual appearance from frame 1, then the temporal diffusion ensures coherent continuation

**Related work to also study**:
- **AnchorSync (2025)**: Explicit "sparse anchor frame editing" + smooth interpolation for *long* videos (1000s of frames)
- **VALA (2025)**: Variational alignment with semantic anchors compressed from keyframe latents

**What to steal**:
> ✅ First-frame-as-anchor paradigm for all AI-style-transfer features  
> ✅ Cache your edited keyframes. Only run expensive AI on keyframes, interpolate between them  
> ✅ This is your solution to the "temporal consistency" long-term challenge

---

### 3.4 Meta SAM2 (`facebookresearch/segment-anything-2`)

**What it is**: Unified model for image AND video segmentation. Real-time object tracking across video frames. Released July 2024.

**How it works**:
- Streaming memory architecture: processes frames sequentially, maintains context across frames
- User provides a prompt (point click, bounding box, or mask) on any frame
- SAM2 tracks the object through the entire video in real-time
- Supports multi-object tracking

**Extensions**:
- **SAM2Long** (GitHub): Enhanced SAM2 for long-video segmentation (reduces error accumulation)

**Why it's your most important dependency**:
> Every "isolate this object" or "apply effect to this person" feature depends on SAM2. Without object isolation, you can't do:
> - "Blur the face on the left"
> - "Change shirt color to red"
> - "Remove the car in the background"
> - "Apply color grade only to the sky"

**Integration pattern**:
```python
# User clicks on "the car" in frame 50
# SAM2 tracks the car through frames 1-500
# Returns per-frame binary masks → compositing layer

sam2_predictor.set_video(video_path)
masks, _, _ = sam2_predictor.predict_video(
    frame_idx=50,
    point_coords=[[x, y]],  # user click
    point_labels=[1],
    track_backward=True
)
# Now apply any operation only within `masks`
```

---

### 3.5 Remotion (`remotion-dev/remotion`)

**What it is**: React-based SDK for creating videos programmatically. Use CSS/Canvas/SVG/WebGL/React to define video structure. FFmpeg renders it server-side.

**Architecture**: react component tree → renders to frames via headless browser → FFmpeg rebundles → video

**Limitations (critical for VIDE)**:
- Code-first: no built-in visual timeline, no drag and drop
- No non-technical users — requires React programming knowledge
- Client-side rendering is experimental, WebCodecs only (Chrome 94+, Firefox 130+, Safari 26+)
- No real-time editing hooks for AI model integration
- Browser throttles `requestAnimationFrame` when tab is backgrounded
- Cross-platform compilation not possible — Tauri relies heavily on native toolchains

**What to steal**:
> ✅ The React component model for your timeline editor frontend — video as a declarative React tree with time as a prop
> ✅ WebCodecs for in-browser preview rendering (fast, no FFmpeg on client)

---

### 3.6 editly (`mifi/editly`) + twick (AI video editor SDK)

**editly**: Declarative video editing API — define a JSON spec → editly outputs a video. Server-side export via FFmpeg. No UX layer.

**twick**: React-based video editor SDK with canvas timeline, drag-and-drop, AI captions (Google Vertex AI), serverless MP4 export.

**Critical constraint in both**:
- Export is constrained to client RAM/CPU/GPU — browser export crashes on large files
- WebCodecs is Chromium-only → Firefox and Safari must use server-side FFmpeg
- In-browser preview is limited, full-res export must go server-side

**What to steal**:
> ✅ Server-side export-over-API pattern: Web app sends all job details to server FFmpeg worker, stream progress back via WebSocket
> ✅ JSON declarative spec format for the entire edit timeline

---

### 3.7 DeepFilterNet (`rikorose/DeepFilterNet`)

**What it is**: Real-time speech enhancement / noise removal. Full-band audio at 48kHz. Latency: 10–20ms.

**Python integration**: `pip install deepfilternet`, `PyDF` Python wrapper for STFT/ISTFT loop.

**Why it matters**: Every user video has background noise. DeepFilterNet is production-ready, one-line Python to run. No GPU needed for inference on CPU. GPU makes it ~5x faster.

**Integration**:
```python
from df.enhance import enhance, init_df, load_audio, save_audio

model, df_state, _ = init_df()
audio, sr = load_audio("input.wav", sr=df_state.sr())
enhanced = enhance(model, df_state, audio)
save_audio("output.wav", enhanced, df_state.sr())
```

> ✅ Steal: Run this on every user-uploaded video automatically as a pre-processing step

---

### 3.8 Real-ESRGAN (`xinntao/Real-ESRGAN`)

**What it is**: AI super-resolution model. Upscales images/videos 2x or 4x with high quality. Particularly good at restoring details in degraded footage.

**How it works**:
1. Extract all frames with FFmpeg
2. Run Real-ESRGAN on each frame (batched, GPU-accelerated with half-precision fp16)
3. Reassemble with FFmpeg + RIFE for temporal consistency

**Models**:
- `RealESRGAN_x4plus` — general photos/footage
- `realesr-animevideov3` — anime/illustration content
- `ncnn-vulkan` variant — runs on any GPU (NVIDIA/AMD/Intel/Mac M-series)

**Production note**: A 720p → 4K upscale is ~4x processing. For a 2-minute clip at 60fps = 7200 frames. Each frame takes ~100ms on RTX 3090 → ~12 min total. **This must be a background job, never synchronous**.

> ✅ Steal: The frame extraction → batch process → reassemble pipeline with RIFE temporal consistency

---

### 3.9 LaMa Inpainting + rembg

**LaMa (`advimman/lama`)**: Large Mask Inpainting using Fast Fourier Convolutions. Fills in missing regions or removes objects with ambient context preservation.

**rembg (`danielgatis/rembg`)**: Background removal using machine learning. Handles hair, semi-transparent objects. CUDA/ROCm GPU support.

**Combined Pipeline for "Remove Object from Video"**:
```
User: "Remove the lamp in the background"
→ SAM2 generates per-frame masks of the lamp
→ LaMa inpaints each frame where the mask is active
→ FFmpeg reassembles the processed frames
→ Temporal consistency pass (RIFE interpolation on non-keyframes)
```

> ✅ `rembg` for background removal in image editor  
> ✅ `LaMa` for object removal / inpainting in both image and video  
> ✅ This combination is your "erase" tool

