## 4. Tech Stack Deep Dive — Every Layer Explained

### 4.1 Language Choices & Why

| Layer | Language | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| API Gateway | **Go 1.22** | Single binary, 50k+ concurrent connections via goroutines, native HTTP/2 + gRPC, fast auth/rate-limiting/routing |
| AI Workers | **Python 3.12** | PyTorch, OpenCV, FFmpeg-python, librosa, SAM2, CLIP — the entire AI/ML stack is Python-native, no competition |
| Desktop Shell | **Rust** | Zero-copy memory model (no expensive copies when processing large video frames), sub-15MB app bundle, Tauri native bindings |
| Frontend | **TypeScript + React 19** | Complex timeline editor, drag-and-drop, WebSocket live preview, TanStack Query for server state |
| Web Framework | **Next.js 15** | SSR for marketing + app shell, React Server Components, API routes |

**Why NOT wasm for video**: WASM is sandboxed — no filesystem access, no GPU (yet), no native codec support. Complex video processing must happen server-side.

**Why NOT Electron for desktop**: 150MB+ bundle, duplicate Chromium, high memory. Tauri uses system WebView2 (Windows) / WebKitGTK (Linux) + Rust backend = <15MB bundle.

---

### 4.2 NLP Intent Pipeline

This is the **core innovation** of the product. When a user types "cut the first 10 seconds, add a fade, boost the bass slightly, and export at 1080p", the system must convert this into a structured execution graph.

#### Two-Stage Pipeline

**Stage 1: LLM Planner** (GPT-4o / Gemini / local Mistral 7B or LLaMA 3.1 8B)
- Input: raw user text + current timeline context (metadata about the loaded video)
- Output: structured JSON operation graph

**Stage 2: Validator + Executor**
- Validate the JSON against the operation schema
- Run a dry-run (validate all parameters are in range, clips exist, etc.)
- Show the user a natural language confirmation: "I'm going to: [trim 0–3s] [add fade] [boost saturation 15%]"
- Wait for user approval
- Execute the DAG

#### Operation Schema JSON Format

```json
{
  "plan_id": "plan_20260319_001",
  "operations": [
    {
      "op": "trim",
      "start": 0,
      "end": 10,
      "action": "remove"
    },
    {
      "op": "transition",
      "type": "fade",
      "target": "cut_point",
      "duration_ms": 500
    },
    {
      "op": "audio_eq",
      "band": "bass",
      "gain_db": 3
    },
    {
      "op": "export",
      "resolution": "1080p",
      "codec": "h264",
      "crf": 18
    }
  ]
}
```

#### Operation Registry (~200 Named Operations)

The LLM is prompted with the full schema. For ambiguous commands, the system asks for clarification before executing. You never train the LLM from scratch — you prompt-engineer a planning layer on top of existing models.

**Example categories**:
- `trim`, `split`, `merge`, `loop` — clip operations
- `fade_in`, `fade_out`, `crossfade`, `dissolve` — transitions
- `color_grade`, `lut_apply`, `saturation`, `brightness`, `contrast` — color
- `denoise_audio`, `eq_bass`, `eq_treble`, `normalize_loudness` — audio
- `remove_background`, `remove_object`, `inpaint`, `style_transfer` — AI operations
- `upscale`, `slow_motion`, `speed_ramp`, `stabilize` — video AI
- `export`, `preview`, `thumbnail` — output operations

#### Local/Offline Support

For privacy-sensitive users and enterprise clients:
- Quantized **Mistral 7B** or **LLaMA 3.1 8B** via `llama.cpp` (4-bit quantization)
- Runs on consumer GPUs with 8GB VRAM
- Smaller distilled versions of SAM2 and CLIP for device-side vision inference
- This is a 6-month engineering effort to get right

---

### 4.3 Video Processing Stack

```mermaid
graph LR
    RAW["Raw Input\nVideo File"] --> DEMUX["Demux\nFFmpeg split\nvideo + audio streams"]
    DEMUX --> VOP["Video Ops\ncut/trim/splice\ncolor grade LUT\ntransitions/effects"]
    DEMUX --> AOP["Audio Ops\nnoise removal\nEQ/level/FX\nsound effects"]
    AI["AI Models\nSAM2 objects\nCLIP scenes"] --> VOP
    VOP --> MUX["Mux + Export\nH.264 / H.265 / AV1\nAAC / FLAC audio"]
    AOP --> MUX
```

**FFmpeg** is the universal foundation — handles virtually every container format and codec. Your Python video worker calls FFmpeg via subprocess or the `ffmpeg-python` library.

**GPU Acceleration**:
- NVIDIA: `NVENC` for encoding, `NVDEC` for decoding (zero-copy via CUDA)
- AMD: `AMF` encoder
- Intel: `QuickSync`
- Linux: `VA-API` for hardware-accelerated decode/encode
- Apple Silicon: `VideoToolbox`

**AI-Powered Video Features**:

| Feature | Model | How |
|---|---|---|
| Scene detection + auto-cut | PySceneDetect + CLIP embeddings | Content-aware scene boundary detection; cluster similar scenes |
| Object tracking + masking | SAM2 | Track objects through video frames via streaming memory |
| Automatic B-roll placement | CLIP embeddings on transcript | Find semantically relevant clips from library at the right moment |
| Color grading | LUT model trained on cinematography datasets | Convert "make it look 70s film" → LUT → FFmpeg LUT filter |
| Slow motion / Frame interpolation | RIFE (Real-time Intermediate Flow Estimation) | Generate intermediate frames between existing frames |
| Video upscaling | Real-ESRGAN | Frame-by-frame upscale with temporal consistency module |
| Video stabilization | OpenCV + vidstab | Optical flow-based stabilization |

---

### 4.4 Image Processing Stack

**Layered approach**:
1. **Pillow** — basic operations (crop, resize, rotate, format conversion)
2. **OpenCV** — complex CV (inpainting, edge detection, perspective correction, object detection, contour finding)
3. **AI models** — for features requiring understanding:
   - **rembg** — background removal (one-line Python, GPU-accelerated)
   - **LaMa** — inpainting / object removal (Fast Fourier Convolutions, production-ready ~2s on T4 GPU)
   - **Real-ESRGAN** — 2x/4x super resolution without quality loss
   - **AdaIN / DiffStyle** — style transfer
   - **SAM2** — object segmentation (with masking → enables selective editing)

**Non-Destructive Principle**: Every operation generates a new layer or a transform node in the DAG, never modifying the original pixels. The edit history is THIS DAG, which can be rewound, branched, or replayed.

**GDPR / Privacy Consideration**: Images and video are processed without being stored permanently when the user opts into ephemeral processing. Delete media after job completes.

---

### 4.5 Audio Processing Stack

| Use Case | Library | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| BPM detection, beat tracking, silence detection | **librosa** | Industry standard audio analysis in Python |
| Professional audio effects (reverb, compression, EQ, pitch shifting) | **pedalboard** (Spotify) | Production-grade, wraps VST3/AU plugins |
| Noise removal, speech enhancement | **DeepFilterNet** | Real-time, 10–20ms latency, 48kHz full-band |
| Background noise removal (RNNoise alternative) | **DeepFilterNet** | Also works via LADSPA plugin on Linux |
| Music generation for background tracks | **MusicGen** (Meta) | Text-to-music generation |
| Sound effects retrieval | **AudioLDM2** | Text-to-audio generation for sound effects |
| Speech recognition (for subtitle/transcript) | **Whisper** (OpenAI) | Best-in-class multilingual ASR |
| Loudness normalization | **pyloudnorm** | EBU R128 standard for broadcast/streaming |

**Audio Pipeline**:
```
User video → FFmpeg extract audio → DeepFilterNet denoise →
librosa analyze (BPM/beats) → pedalboard effects chain →
pyloudnorm normalize → FFmpeg re-embed into video
```

---

### 4.6 Distributed Job Queue Architecture

#### Why a job queue?
GPU inference is expensive. A single "remove background from this 2-minute video" job using SAM2 frame-by-frame costs real money. You need:
- **Batch queuing**: Multiple users' jobs shouldn't block each other
- **Tiered processing**: Cheap model for preview → expensive model for export
- **Result caching**: Same clip + operation → cached result (saves GPU cost)
- **Worker crash safety**: Job state persists in Redis even if worker dies

```mermaid
graph TB
    API["API Gateway\n(Go)"] --> Q["BullMQ Queues\n(Redis-backed)"]
    Q --> |"preview jobs"| WP1["Preview Workers\n(cheap models, fast)"]
    Q --> |"export jobs"| WP2["Export Workers\n(expensive models, slow)"]
    Q --> |"AI jobs"| WP3["AI Workers\n(GPU pods)"]
    WP1 --> WS["WebSocket\n(stream progress)"]
    WP2 --> S3["MinIO / S3\n(output files)"]
    WP3 --> CACHE["Redis Cache\n(result caching)"]
    WS --> CLIENT["Client App"]
```

#### Queue Types

| Queue | Purpose | Workers | Model Tier |
|---|---|---|---|
| `preview` | 480p low-latency previews for timeline scrubbing | 10+ lightweight | Fast, cheap |
| `ai-operations` | SAM2 segmentation, DeepFilterNet, LaMa | 2–5 GPU workers | Expensive |
| `export` | Full-res FFmpeg render, Codec encode | 3–6 CPU workers | CPU-heavy |
| `audio` | DeepFilterNet, Whisper transcription | 2–4 CPU/GPU | Medium |

#### BullMQ vs Kafka

| | BullMQ (Redis) | Kafka |
|---|---|---|
| Use for | Standard job management, retry, priority, rate-limiting | Large-scale event streaming, audit log, replay |
| Latency | Low (ms) | Higher (batch-oriented) |
| Persistence | Redis AOF/RDB | Log-based, infinite retention |
| Language support | Node.js + Python natively | All languages via client libs |
| When to use | Start here. 95% of use cases. | When you need event replay, fan-out to multiple consumers, 10k+ jobs/sec |

**Start with BullMQ. Add Kafka later for event streaming (audit log of all edits, stream to analytics).**

---

### 4.7 Storage Architecture

| Store | Technology | What's Stored |
|---|---|---|
| Raw + Proxy Media | **MinIO / S3** | Original uploads (never mutated), 480p proxies, rendered exports |
| Metadata + Users + Projects | **PostgreSQL** | User accounts, project records, operation DAGs (as JSON), edit history |
| Cache + Sessions + Queue State | **Redis** | Job states, auth tokens, result cache (TTL-based) |
| Vector Embeddings | **Qdrant** | CLIP embeddings of all clips for semantic search ("find clip with sunset") |

#### Media Lifecycle
```
Upload → S3 (raw) → Generate proxy (480p) → S3 (proxy)
Edit → Operations stored in PostgreSQL (DAG) — never touch raw
Export → Read raw from S3 → Apply DAG operations → Render → S3 (output)
```

#### Why Qdrant (Vector DB)?
- Semantic search across footage library: "show me all clips with people laughing"
- B-roll suggestion: transcript text → embed → find matching clips via cosine similarity
- Style matching: embed reference image → find visually similar clips

---

### 4.8 Frontend — Web App

**Stack**: React 19 + Next.js 15 + TypeScript + Tailwind CSS + Zustand + TanStack Query + React DnD Kit

**Key UI Components**:
1. **Timeline Editor** — drag-and-drop clips, multi-track audio/video, frame scrubbing
2. **NL Command Bar** — text input → shows AI-parsed plan → confirm → execute
3. **Properties Panel** — shows current operation parameters, adjustable sliders
4. **Preview Window** — WebSocket-driven real-time low-res preview
5. **Edit History** — visual DAG tree, undo/redo, branch from any point

**Real-time Preview Architecture**:
```
User scrubs timeline
→ React sends WebSocket message: { clip_id, timestamp, operations[] }
→ Go gateway routes to a preview worker
→ Worker renders 480p proxy frame (fast)
→ Streams JPEG frame back via WebSocket
→ React displays in preview window
```

**Why TanStack Query**: Server state management for all API calls (project data, job status polling, operation results). Handles caching, background refetching, optimistic updates.

**Why React DnD Kit**: Modern, performance-oriented drag-and-drop for the timeline. The legacy `react-beautiful-dnd` is deprecated.

**E2E Encryption Option**: For enterprise clients, encrypt project data client-side before sending to server. Server stores encrypted blobs. Client decrypts locally. This handles GDPR.

---

### 4.9 Desktop App — Tauri 2.0

**Why Tauri over Electron**:
- Electron: ships its own Chromium (150MB+), Node.js, high memory usage
- Tauri: uses system WebView (WebView2 on Windows, WebKitGTK on Linux, WebKit on macOS), Rust backend → <15MB bundle

**Architecture**:
```
Web frontend (React — shared codebase with web app)
     ↕ Tauri IPC (invoke/emit)
Rust backend (handles:)
  - Local file system access (read/write video files directly)
  - FFmpeg subprocess management
  - Local AI inference (llama.cpp, SAM2 small, CLIP small)
  - Native OS notifications, tray, auto-update
  - Hardware detection (GPU, RAM, available VRAM)
```

**Offline Mode**:
- Local LLaMA 3.1 8B (4-bit quantized via llama.cpp) for NLP planning
- Local SAM2-small for object segmentation
- Local DeepFilterNet for audio denoising
- Local FFmpeg for all video/audio processing
- Cloud sync optional — upload to server for heavy AI features

**Cross-Platform Build Pipeline** (non-negotiable from day 1):
```yaml
# GitHub Actions — must build all 3 platforms
jobs:
  build-windows:
    runs-on: windows-latest
    steps: [tauri build]
  build-macos:
    runs-on: macos-latest  # Apple Silicon
    steps: [tauri build, codesign]
  build-linux:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps: [tauri build, appimage]
```

---

### 4.10 Infrastructure & GPU Nodes

**Cloud Deployment**: Web app + API deploy to any cloud (AWS, GCP, self-hosted). Docker containers, orchestrated with Kubernetes.

**GPU Node Options**:
| GPU | VRAM | Best For | Cost (est.) |
|---|---|---|---|
| NVIDIA A10G | 24GB | SAM2, LaMa, Real-ESRGAN | ~$0.75/hr |
| NVIDIA A100 (40GB) | 40GB | Large model inference, batch export | ~$2.50/hr |
| NVIDIA L4 | 24GB | Cost-efficient inference | ~$0.54/hr |
| AMD MI300X | 192GB | HPC workloads | ~$3.50/hr |

**GPU Cost Optimization**:
- **Result caching**: Same clip + same operation = cached. Saves 40–60% GPU cost in practice.
- **Tiered processing**: Always run on cheapest model that achieves acceptable quality for preview. Only use expensive model on final export.
- **Spot instances**: Use AWS Spot / GCP Preemptible for batch export jobs (70% cheaper; must handle preemption gracefully by checkpointing job state in Redis).

**Monitoring Stack**: Prometheus + Grafana for metrics. GPU utilization, job queue depth, worker health, latency percentiles.

---

## 5. Short-Term Challenges (0–6 Months) & Solutions

### 5.1 NLP Command Ambiguity ⚠️ HARDEST PROBLEM
**Problem**: "Make it cinematic", "clean up the audio", "fix the colors" are meaningless without a disambiguation layer. Every existing tool either ignores this or punts to the user with a form.

**Solution**:
1. **Confirmation before execute**: System parses command → generates natural-language plan → shows user "I'm going to: [trim 0–3s] [add fade] [boost saturation 15%]" → waits for approval
2. **Ambiguity detection**: If the LLM confidence is < threshold, ask a clarifying question ("Do you mean the bass in the background music, or the voiceover?")
3. **Operation schema validation**: All generated JSON validates against the ~200-operation schema. Invalid operations → ask for clarification, never execute blindly
4. **This gives you a natural undo model**: The user approved the plan. If the result isn't what they wanted, they can see exactly what ran and revert it.

### 5.2 GPU Cost Per Request
**Problem**: A single "remove background from this 2-minute video" job using SAM2 frame-by-frame costs real money. At scale, this compounds fast.

**Solution**:
1. **Batch queuing**: Never process a request immediately if a similar one is queued. Batch similar operations
2. **Result caching**: `hash(clip_id + operation_params)` → check Redis before running inference. Cache results with TTL
3. **Tiered processing**: Low-res/cheap model for preview (instant), expensive model only on export button press
4. **Spot instances**: 70% cheaper. Handle preemption via job checkpointing in Redis
5. **Model distillation**: Where possible, fine-tune smaller versions of models for your most frequent operations

### 5.3 Large File Latency
**Problem**: A 10GB 4K video file takes minutes to upload, and processing takes even longer. This is a UX killer.

**Solution** (industry standard):
1. **Proxy editing**: Immediately generate 480p proxy on upload (cheap). Show editing UI using proxy. Only access full-res on final export. This is how Premiere Pro works.
2. **Chunked upload**: Upload video in chunks (uppy.js or tus protocol). Resumable, parallel chunk upload.
3. **Progressive loading**: Start showing timeline scrubbing while video is still uploading (stream from partially uploaded file)
4. **Smart caching**: Cache rendered preview frames by timestamp. Scrubbing the same point twice = instant the second time.

### 5.4 Cross-Platform Desktop Build Pipeline
**Problem**: Tauri relies heavily on native libraries and toolchains. Meaningful cross-compilation is not possible — you must have 3 separate CI runners.

**Solution**:
1. GitHub Actions with 3 build runners: Windows (windows-latest), macOS Apple Silicon (macos-latest), Linux (ubuntu-latest)
2. All 3 runners from day 1 — adding a runner later after codebase grows is extremely painful (native library incompatibilities compound)
3. Code signing from day 1: Apple notarization + Microsoft EV cert
4. Single shared React codebase between web and desktop (Tauri just wraps it)

### 5.5 Browser Export Compatibility
**Problem**: WebCodecs (for in-browser video encoding) is Chromium-only. Firefox and Safari must use server-side FFmpeg.

**Solution**:
- In-browser preview: WebCodecs + Mediabunny (fast, Chromium only)
- Export: Always route to server-side FFmpeg worker, regardless of browser  
- Never let the frontend generate the final export. Frontend is for preview only.

---

## 6. Long-Term Challenges (6–36 Months) & Solutions

### 6.1 Temporal Consistency in AI Video Edits
**Problem**: AI style transfer or object manipulation across 300–500 frames creates flickering — subtle differences between frames that look deeply wrong.

**Solutions**:
1. **AnyV2V paradigm**: Edit first frame → I2V model with temporal injection propagates edits
2. **Keyframe anchoring**: Run expensive AI only on keyframes (every 30th frame), RIFE interpolate intermediate frames
3. **AnchorSync approach** (2025 research): For long videos (1000+ frames), sparse anchor frame editing + smooth interpolation
4. **Optical flow consistency**: Use optical flow between frames to warp the previous edit result to the next frame — much cheaper than running full model again

### 6.2 Offline & Local AI Inference
**Problem**: Privacy-conscious users and enterprise clients cannot upload footage to cloud servers. GPU cost also becomes a problem at scale.

**Solution Timeline**:
- Month 6–9: llama.cpp for local NLP planner (Mistral 7B, 4-bit, 8GB VRAM)
- Month 9–12: SAM2-small distilled model for local object segmentation
- Month 12–18: Distilled CLIP for local semantic search
- Month 18+: Custom quantized models for device inference on Apple Silicon (Core ML), NVIDIA (TensorRT), AMD (ROCm)

**Toolchain**: llama.cpp (C++ backend, Python bindings), `ctransformers` for easy Python model loading, ONNX Runtime for cross-hardware model export

### 6.3 Data Privacy & GDPR Compliance
**Problem**: As soon as European users upload personal video footage (containing faces = biometric data), you're handling regulated data.

**Architecture Responses**:
1. **Ephemeral processing**: All media is deleted from server after job completes (configurable TTL, default 24h)
2. **E2E encryption option**: Enterprise tier — client encrypts footage before upload, server stores encrypted blobs, client decrypts results
3. **On-device processing**: Desktop app with local AI means footage never leaves user's computer
4. **GDPR data controls**: Export all project data, delete all data — user-accessible controls in settings
5. **Audit log**: Every operation logged with timestamp, user ID, operation type. Never log raw media content.

### 6.4 Real-Time Collaboration
**Problem**: Think Google Docs for video — two users trimming the same clip in different ways cannot be trivially merged. Timeline edits are inherently non-commutative.

**Research Direction**:
- CRDTs work for text but timeline edits need significant adaptation (non-commutative operations)
- **Operational Transform (OT)** for video: transform an operation against another to resolve conflicts. Existing academic work exists but is not production-ready.
- **Short-term pragmatic solution**: Lock-based editing. One user edits at a time. Others can comment.
- **Long-term**: Custom CRDT for timeline data structures — this is a research problem, not just engineering.

### 6.5 Model Version Drift
**Problem**: Every time an upstream model (SAM2, CLIP, GPT-4o) releases a new version, your carefully tuned prompts and operation schemas may break or produce different outputs.

**Solution**:
1. **Model version pinning**: Lock exact model versions in all worker containers (`SAM2-hiera-large-v1.0`, not `SAM2-latest`)
2. **Regression test suite**: Golden set of 100 reference outputs (clips + operations → expected outputs). Run on every model upgrade. SSIM + VMAF metrics for video quality.
3. **Shadow model testing**: Run new model version in parallel (on 5% of traffic) before full rollout. Compare outputs statistically.
4. **Prompt versioning**: Store all LLM prompts in version-controlled config files, separate from code. Prompt changes go through the same review process as code changes.

---

## 7. Best Practices — Synthesized From the Ecosystem

### NLP / AI Layer Best Practices

| Practice | Why |
|---|---|
| **Confirm before execute** | Show parsed plan, get user approval. Prevents trust destruction from bad edits. Gives you a natural undo hook. |
| **Dry-run mode** | Validate the JSON operation schema before running any model. Catch parameter errors before spending GPU |
| **Model version pinning** | Freeze model versions in worker containers. Never use `latest` tag in production. |
| **~200 named operations** | Don't let the LLM freestyle — restrict to a schema. Every operation in the registry is tested, bounded, undoable. |

### Video / Media Pipeline Best Practices

| Practice | Why |
|---|---|
| **Proxy editing always** | 480p for edit → full-res for export. This is industry standard. Premiere Pro, DaVinci. Never skip this. |
| **Non-destructive DAG** | Never mutate original media. Store operations as a graph. Every node is revertible. |
| **Keyframe anchoring** | AI edits on keyframes only → RIFE interpolation. Reduces GPU cost 10x, eliminates flicker. |
| **Server-side export only** | Browser can preview (WebCodecs). Final export must go to FFmpeg server worker. Never trust browser for production output. |

### Desktop / Cross-Platform Best Practices

| Practice | Why |
|---|---|
| **CI/CD from day 1** | Windows + Mac + Linux runners. Adding a platform later breaks everything due to native dependency hell. |
| **Code signing from day 1** | Apple notarization + Microsoft EV cert. Without this, users get "untrusted developer" warnings. Takes 2–4 weeks to set up. |
| **Shared React codebase** | Web app and Tauri desktop share the same frontend. Tauri just wraps it with IPC bridges for native features. |

### Infrastructure Best Practices

| Practice | Why |
|---|---|
| **Result caching** | `hash(clip + op + params)` → Redis cache. Saves 40–60% GPU cost. Same op on same clip = free. |
| **Stateless workers** | Workers hold no state. All state in Redis/PostgreSQL. Can kill/restart/scale any worker pod at any time. |
| **Tiered processing** | Cheap model for preview → expensive model for export. Never run expensive inference on a preview frame. |
| **Spot instances** | 70% cheaper for batch export jobs. Handle preemption via Redis job checkpointing. |

### Security & Privacy Best Practices

| Practice | Why |
|---|---|
| **Ephemeral processing** | Delete media from server after job completes (configurable, default 24h). Required for GDPR. |
| **E2E encryption option** | Enterprise clients need footage to stay encrypted end-to-end. |
| **GDPR data controls** | Export all data, delete all data — user-facing settings. Required for EU users. |

### Testing Best Practices (AI-Specific)

| Practice | Why |
|---|---|
| **Golden set evals** | 100 reference outputs. Run SSIM + VMAF quality metrics on every model upgrade. |
| **Shadow model testing** | New model runs in parallel on 5% of traffic before full rollout. |
| **SSIM / VMAF metrics** | Measure video quality numerically. Human review doesn't scale. |

